<h2>How to Use These Questions</h2>

<p>
  Having 100+ questions is great. Knowing how to use them is what makes the difference. Here are a few practical tips to get the most out of this list:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Do not marathon through them.</strong> Pick two or three per sitting. The goal is conversation, not completion. The best moments often come from the follow-up questions that arise naturally — not from checking items off a list.</li>
  <li><strong>Take turns answering first.</strong> If one person always goes first, the other starts anchoring their answers. Switch it up so you both get to share without being influenced.</li>
  <li><strong>Write down the answers that surprise you.</strong> You will forget the details faster than you think. Use the shared notes feature in <a href="https://apps.apple.com/app/id6758024356" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-primary hover:underline">OurCouple</a> to save your favorite answers and revisit them later.</li>
  <li><strong>No judgment, no scorekeeping.</strong> If your partner gets a question "wrong" about you, do not make them feel bad about it. The point is discovery, not testing. Laugh about it and fill in the gaps together.</li>
  <li><strong>Revisit the same questions over time.</strong> Your answers will change. That is the point. A question about your dreams asked today will have a different answer in a year. Noticing the evolution is one of the most rewarding parts.</li>
  <li><strong>Create a ritual around it.</strong> Use one question as a conversation starter every date night. Or send each other a daily question through a messaging app. Consistency matters more than volume.</li>
