<h2>Why Knowing Your Partner Matters</h2>

<p>
  This is not just a feel-good exercise. Relationship research consistently backs up the idea that knowledge of your partner is one of the strongest predictors of relationship health. Dr. John Gottman, whose research has spanned over four decades, calls this building "love maps" — detailed knowledge of your partner's inner world, their worries, their joys, their history, and their hopes.
</p>

<p>
  Couples with detailed love maps navigate conflict better because they understand the context behind their partner's reactions. They handle life transitions more smoothly because they know what their partner values and fears. And they report higher levels of intimacy — not because they agree on everything, but because they feel truly seen.
</p>

<p>
  The opposite is also true. When couples stop being curious about each other, they start making assumptions. And assumptions are where resentment quietly takes root. You assume your partner knows you are stressed. They assume you are fine because you have not said anything. Both of you are wrong, and neither of you is asking.
</p>

<p>
  Taking a how well do you know your partner quiz — or simply working through a list like this one together — is a low-stakes way to interrupt that cycle. It is a reminder that the person sitting across from you is still full of surprises, if you are willing to look.
</p>

